defaultHowever, there have been significant delays 
defaultto the key policie
defaults which aim to drive the strategic frameworks established by these overarching Government strategies. In particular, the Renewable Heat Incentive is now three years behind its originally proposed implementation date; with the domestic sch
defaulteme and the revised non-domestic tariffs both due to
default come into force in April 2013. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIndustry confidence has been damaged by the delays to the policy, and will inevitably delay scaling-up supply chains until they have certainty over final tariffs and impl
defaultementation dates. 
defaultThe impact that policy announcements have on the market can be seen from the Ofgem RHI deployment figures; there was a 90% increase in enquiries about the RHI to Ofgem in Jan-March 2013, the quarter after the September 2012 consultations 
default(which closed in December 2012) and a three times
default increase in
default the number of RHI payments made (£5.1m to £1.5m). 
default&#xa0;
defaultI
defaultt is very important that the Government keep t
defaulto their projected timelines. In particular, Air to Water Heat Pumps were originally consulted upon in the New Technologies consultation of September 2012, in what was understood to be a “fast track” to their integration into the RHI scheme. However, a prop
defaultosed tariff for Air Heat Pumps in the commercial scheme was only recently announced (of 2.5p/kWh). With commercial installations taking up to 6 months to specify and agree, it is vital that the Government announces this as the final tariff level in the aut
defaultumn, so that we can be ready to install the first new commercial air 
defaultto water 
defaultheat pumps in spring 2014.  
default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition, the Green Deal, the Government’s flagship energy efficiency scheme for the domestic market (at present) has also had a low
default uptake again
defaultst its projections (just over 300 Green Deal Plans are planned or pending as of July 2013, see below).
