defaulte UK heating sector, and examine innovative new solutions to the community energy problem using technologies other than CHP. We were therefore are pleased 
defaultthat the Government recently consulted on the development of a Community Energy Strategy, to which we
default have offered evidence.
default&#xa0;
defaultThere has been significant evidence 
defaultp
defaultut forward to suggest that community heating should be a priority for the UK Government going forward, as the 2013 Heat Strategy makes clear (below). Government models suggest that up to 20% of 
defaultUK domestic heat demand could be met by community heating schemes by 2030, with such schemes offering energy efficiency benefits over traditional individual heating systems:
defaultIn particular, the 2009 Poyry report suggested that heat networks could offer b
defaultenefits to urban communities, where heat demand was concentrated. Deployment to this kind of property could halve carbon emissions compared with using existing technologies.
default We believe that recognising 
defaultground and 
defaultair source heat pumps as a technology whic
defaulth could deliver this kind of community heating scheme efficiently and cost-effectively, would help drive the deployment of this kind of collective heating system.
default&#xa0;
defaultOur own research highlights the opportunity for policymakers of recognising heat pump system
defaults for deployment as community heating in low and high rise flats in the UK, to replace existing heating technologies.  
defaultFor the purposes of our research, we defined “low rise” as having 6 storeys or less and “high rise” as having more than 6 storeys. 
